project_info.prj_overview:
Overview The work plan continues a variety of essential NPS management and implementation efforts that will be undertaken by staff within DEC¿s Watershed Management Division. The efforts by 319 funded staff within DEC-WSMD are directly related to the delivery, deployment and use of about $2.1 million in State of Vermont capital funds allocated for NPS implementation (specifically funds under SFY2013 Ecosystem Restoration Program). This work plan also continues a successful pass through program to enable and further assist NPS implementation by the Vermont AAF&M. DEC considers the pass through program to AAF&M to be a critical element in nurturing partnerships, pursuing the watershed approach and targeting implementation resources to priority agricultural NPS areas. This work plan is consistent with the 2013 Performance Partnership Agreement between DEC and EPA. Vermont's total FFY2013 Section 319 funding amount shown above reflects close to a $50K reduction in funding when compared to the final amount awarded to Vermont under FFY2012 Section 319.
Objectives Pollution and the threat of pollution from NPSs are responsible for the vast majority of problems and potential problems confronting Vermont¿s water resources. NPSs impact the chemical, physical and biological components of the state¿s rivers, lakes and wetlands (see 2012 VT 305b Water Quality Assessment Report and to the various year 2012 listings of waters). To effectively counter those circumstances, DEC will utilize a significant portion of the FFY2013 319 funding award to carry out specific NPS activities and NPS implementation-based programs on a statewide basis. The NPS-related programs which will utilize 2013 319 funds are shown under methods below.
Methods The NPS-related programs which utilized 2013 319 funds, including the approximate level of human resource needs requirements, are as follows: - NPS program management/administration & support - 0.9 FTE - Stormwater management/control ¿ 0.85 FTE - 303e river basin planning for NPS implementation - 5 FTE - River & river corridor management ¿ 6.2 FTE - Lake & pond watershed & shoreline management ¿ 0.65 FTE

project_info.prj_title: use of 2014 319 by AAF+M
project_info.prj_complete_comments: project represents use of 2014 319 by AAF+M
project_info.pst_comment: project completed
project_info.prj_overview:
Overview The Project assisted by 319 grant funds concerns the following elements: A) Agricultural BMP Cost Share Grant Program B) ARS Technical Assistance Program with VACD C) Groundwater + Drinking Water Protection Program D) Agricultural Engineering + Waste Management Assistance Program E) Agricultural Watershed Planning + Implementation
Objectives Agriculture, Food and Markets (AAF+M) conducts a comprehensive agricultural WQ program to prevent and reduce the pollution of surface water and groundwater resources from agricultural sources. The Agricultural Water Quality Program is operated in accordance with the statutory authority granted to AAF+M and a NPS MOU between DEC and AAF+M. The NPS Program MOU is drafted in accordance with 6 V.S.A. Chapter 215, Section 4810. The original NPS Program MOU was signed in 1993.
Methods A. BMP Cost Share Grant Program The Agricultural Water Quality Program and the grant support the position of the BMP Cost Share Grant Coordinator at approximately 0.25 Full Time Equivalent (FTE). B. ARS Technical Assistance Program The Agricultural Water Quality program maintains an agreement between AAF+M and the Vermont Association of Conservation Districts (VACD) to support the ARS Program. The current grant supports ARS personnel in Orleans, Otter Creek, White River, and Rutland Natural Resource Conservation Districts. At the current level of funding, the 319 grant supports the equivalent of slightly less than one full time position (0.8 FTE). C. Groundwater and Drinking Water Protection Program The WQ sampling and laboratory analysis conducted by AAF+M supports the compliance operations of the AAP Program, the nutrient management and enforcement activities of the Medium Farm Operations and the Large Farm Operations Programs, the ARS Technical Assistance Program, and the on-farm risk assessments of the AEM Program. The 2014 work plan for 319 grant funds supports the position of the Soil Scientist at approximately 0.34 FTE. D. Agricultural Engineering & Waste Management Assistance Program The Agricultural Water Quality Program and the grant support the position of the Agricultural Engineer at 0.31 FTE. E. Agricultural Watershed Planning & Implementation. AAF+M anticipates integrating the Statewide Surface Water Management Strategy into the process of implementing agricultural BMPs by using monitoring and assessment data developed by DEC to target watersheds in which agricultural impairments are prevalent. AAF+M will participate in scoping meetings to develop an outline identifying the agricultural stressors, next steps and the details of how to approach the tactical planning process. AAF+M also plans on participating in the development of the tactical basin plans as they relate to agriculture through the knowledge and expertise of the medium and large farm regulatory staff, AAP field agents, ARS and Land Treatment and Conservation Planners, as applicable for specific watersheds. AAF+M will complete the tactical planning process for agricultural water quality aspects of a river basin (or portion thereof) selected and mutually agreed upon by DEC and AAF+M.

Overview Purchase four manure flow rate meters and install on custom operator spreading units. Custom operators with meters must attend class focused on precision nutrient management hosted by UVM Extension. UVM Extension will manage the use of the equipment.
Objectives Better manage agricultural wastes and nutrients. Educate certain farmers in targeted areas. Further advance aspects affecting precision feed management.
Methods Custom operators receiving manure flow rate meters will record details on applications (ie date, farm and field location, amount and rate applied). Farmers located in previously mapped critical source areas (CSA) of Missisquoi River basin will have highest priority for this task. Through other workshops, custom operators and other contacts of the Farmer¿s Watershed Alliance and UVM Extension, work with a sufficient number of farmers to implement at least 5,000 acres of precision manure management and implement feed management practices on four farms. Priority areas for this task are St. Albans Bay watershed, CSAs in Missisquoi River basin and impaired waters impaired by agricultural runoff within Franklin County. Collect information on pre- and post-manure rates, crop yields and cost savings from at least ten farms to informally compare their experience with precision manure management. Precision Feed Management information will be collected from four farms. Information will include pre- and post-rations, nutrient reduction, and cost savings. Develop a forum for these farmers to share their experiences

Overview Identify and work with up to 10 farms in the Missisquoi River basin having lands/fields previously mapped as `critical source areas¿ (CSA) and one farm in the St. Albans Bay watershed that are willing and eager to reduce nutrient and sediment loading. Implementation could include: native tree species planting on stable banks, improved drainage ditch maintenance following the State¿s guidance document and soil erosion treatment that could treat for gully erosion, flood chute erosion, and sheet erosion. Provide feedback and input on enhancing ANR¿s guidance document on ditch building and maintenance. Feedback/input will be submitted to DEC, Watershed Management Division. Work with one (or more) farmers agreeable to improved drainage ditch maintenance. Install at least one high profile/readily visible demonstration site (ideally within one or more of priority areas in task 1 above) following the ANR guidance document: Maintaining Surface Water Drainage Ditches. Compare/contrast time and material cost concerning ditch work done following specifications in ANR guidance document against traditional ditch maintenance practices (ie vertical sidewalls, ¿V¿ bottoms, no check dams).

project_info.prj_complete_comments: original end date 12/1/14 amended to 12/1/15
project_info.pst_comment: Project resulted in a tiered rain garden on town owned land at intersection of Rt116 and Silver Street. Area draining to rain garden is 6.7 acres with 39% impervious cover. Rain garden provides rain runoff storage (0.3 ac-ft) and infiltration that expected to remove 87% sediment and 34% total phosphorus from stormwater. project_info.prj_overview:
Overview There are 2 components to this project - Part A. Route 116/Silver Street Raingarden Implementation Project (Phase II: Project Implementation) - Hydrology modeling identified that the subwatershed containing the intersection of Route 116 and Silver Street generates a large runoff volume due to large amount of impervious cover and limited storage and infiltration. A conceptual design and preliminary budget for a tiered raingarden was developed on town-owned land at the corner of Route 116 and Silver Street, a high priority area also identified in the initial stormwater infrastructure project. Part B. Patrick Brook Stormwater Treatment Feasibility and Preliminary Design (Phase 1: Project Feasibility Analysis) - Several of the Patrick Brook subwatersheds were identified as having degraded geomorphic condition and a high priority for stormwater mitigation. One potential treatment location was identified next to Mechanicsville Road at the base of the cemetery. A detention area at this location would serve as channel overflow during storm events and detain runoff from the cemetery hillside.
Objectives Develop design for improved stormwater runoff management at 2 sites. Reduce NPS stormwater discharges.
Methods Part A - Additional work is necessary to complete the design to fit the design within existing infrastructure, utilities, and planned sidewalk project. Detailed elevation and utility information is required for final design. LCA will use grant funds to cover the additional data collection, engineering final design, construction oversight, and construction. The Town of Hinesburg will provide excavation labor and equipment and ongoing maintenance of the stormwater treatment system. Part B - The location of this detention area is upstream of stream geomorphic segment T4.02 that has poor geomorphic condition and T4.01, which has significant impervious surface and is therefore vulnerable to stormwater runoff. This site was visited in the field and appears to be a good location for a constructed wetland. LCA will use grant funding for project development including data collection, an alternatives analysis of possible stormwater treatment options, preliminary engineering design, and development of a preliminary cost opinion. Two part project is considered to constitute watershed based plan implementation effort in light of Basin 5 water quality management plan (2009) and BMP scenario tool associated with Lake Champlain TMDL being developed by EPA-Region 1.

project_info.prj_title: Poultney High School stormwater management (PMNRCD)
project_info.pst_comment: 3 large bioretention / rain gardens were installed within an existing parking lot at the high school. Project was deisgned to capture, infiltrate and treat stormwater runoff from school rooftops and parking lot. Combined, the rain gardens treat stormwater runoff from 0.89 acres of imprevious surfaces with the potential to treat over 130,000 cubic feet of stormwater volume each year.
project_info.prj_overview:
Overview Project is to reduce untreated stormwater runoff and address water quality concerns in the Poultney River. Poultney High School lies approximately 500 feet north of the edge of the Poultney River. The parking lot and school bus holding area is a large impervious surface connected by a patchwork drainage system at the rear of the building, creating stormwater runoff that directly affects the river¿s water quality.
Objectives Improve stormwater management by reducing surface flows and NPS pollutant discharge thru infiltration.
Methods To address this issue, PM-NRCD will re-route 4 downspouts, two of which currently are not connected, on the western end of the building to a bio-retention area of approximately 1,000 square feet, enlarge an existing grassy area to a bio-retention area of approximately 1,200 square feet to treat the runoff from the largest parking area that is already graded to flow to the existing area (an existing catch basin will be slightly raised to promote detention and act as an overflow structure), convert a pipe discharge site to a bio-retention area on the east end of the parking lot of approximately 750 square feet and install a grated trench approximately 150 feet long from north to south in the incoming traffic flow area to trap any fluids from vehicles and pipe them to an oil-water separator that would then be connected to an existing catch basin. Project uses bio-retention systems to remove a wide range of potentially existing pollutants, such as suspended solids, nutrients, metals, hydrocarbons, and bacteria from stormwater runoff. These systems utilize native non-invasive vegetation and soil media to collect, filter and/or infiltrate runoff prior to discharge to the groundwater table or receiving water. These practices are typical for small catchment areas and have an under drain and/or an overflow system to divert larger flows above the systems design capacity. PMNRCD project noted above is considered to constitute watershed based plan implementation efforts in light of Otter Creek basin plan (2012) and the BMP scenario tool associated with the Lake Champlain TMDL being developed by EPA-Region 1.
project_info.lreduction_comments: According to project consultant, stormwater runoff from 0.89 acres of impervious surface is routed to one of three bioretention areas for treatment. project_info.prj_overview:
Overview Project will serve to improve water quality in the lower Missisquoi River and Lake Champlain by treating stormwater runoff from a portion of the downtown area in Swanton Village. Village will complete final design and the first phase of construction of an underground stormwater system in Marble Mill Park.
Objectives Improve WQ by treating stormwater volumes created by impervious surfaces within a portion of the village.
Methods The system will include underground detention and recharge galleries with pre-treatment by a hydrodynamic separator. Phase 1 of construction includes installation of the hydrodynamic separator to allow for removal of a large percentage of the solids before some portion of higher flows would be discharged and the remaining portion detained in the underground cells. Once constructed, the project will treat stormwater from over 39.5 acres of developed land.

project_info.prj_title: Sherman Hollow Brook Stream Restoration
project_info.prj_complete_comments: this state funded NPS project is identified in conjunction with "leveraging"
project_info.prj_overview:
Overview Project will help mediate impacts to WQ and the stream channel from a flood event to the tributary of Sherman Hollow Brook that flows through Grantee¿s property. This project will help meet the goals of restoring and protecting waterways from unregulated NPS runoff and erosion.
Objectives Reduce stream flow energy; maintain integrity of stream channel; improve habitat conditions.
Methods A series of step pools will be built within the stream bed. These pools are effective at energy dissipation and can reduce flow velocity and erosion potential. The design, which takes into account and prepares for the likelihood of more frequent and intense storms, will accommodate 100 year flood waters and as such it will prevent further erosion and sedimentation from occurring. Step pools are similar to natural items in a healthy stream such as large woody debris or root wads and they help create habitat used by fish, invertebrates, amphibians and other aquatic and terrestrial species. The area will be monitored for invasive species and project viability. Improved road and parking lot drainage will reduce road sediments/nutrients/chemicals from going directly into the stream.

status_history.pst_comment: BOVM stabilized an actively eroding gully caused by flood event in 2013. Flood event also destabilized town road culvert and caused erosion of nearby road & museum parking lot. Construction of the project was completed summer 2015. Add'l planting to occur in spring 2016. Stabilized gully was about 270 feet long and involved 0.25 acres.

project_info.prj_title: Stormwater Reduction in the East Creek Watershed
project_info.prj_complete_comments: this state funded NPS project is identified in conjunction with "leveraging"
project_info.prj_overview:
Overview The project involves 2 retrofit effort: Green Streets at Preville Avenue and Bioretention at Giorgetti Park. Both are located in the East Creek watershed and both have been identified in the final Stormwater Master Plan for Tenney Brook/East Creek by Watershed Consulting Associates (July 2014). The sites are areas with existing stormwater problems with potential for stormwater retrofit.
Objectives Improve management of stormwater flows; reduce stormwater pollutant contribution; serve as a local demonstration and education effort for area residents.
Methods 1) Preville Ave. Project: A bike path and green stormwater infrastructure practice will be integrated into Preville Avenue by narrowing the vehicle travel width. The project will serve to infiltrate and filter stormwater from the road surface and surrounding properties, thereby reducing stormwater volume and pollutant discharge to East Creek. Beyond the water quality benefits, the project will have a very positive community and aesthetic benefit, by creating an attractive corridor for residents and city visitors. The project will serve as a green streets model, one that is catching on nationwide but is relatively absent thus far in Vermont. The project has been identified in the Tenney Brook/East Creek Stormwater Master Plan as a high priority for retrofit. Under the scope of the Stormwater Master Plan, the site has been surveyed and the feasibility of the suggested approach has been confirmed. Under the proposed scope of work, the NRCD will develop a final design for the Green Street project to integrate the new bike lane and ¿green gutter¿ type Green Stormwater Infrastructure system. The project will then be implemented. 2) Giorgetti Arena Project: This project will mitigate a severe uncontrolled stormwater runoff problem which has resulted in erosion and pollution discharge directly to the East Creek, as well as a continual maintenance burden for the City of Rutland. The project site has scored as high priority in the Tenney Brook/East Creek Stormwater Master Plan for retrofit given the magnitude of the existing issues. As part of the ongoing master planning efforts, a preliminary design has been developed for a large scale bio-retention system that would manage runoff from the parking lot as well as a portion of Preville Avenue. Bio-retention system will retain, infiltrate, and filter runoff that presently flows through a highly eroded ditch directly to East Creek. As part of this project, runoff contributing to this ditch would be eliminated or greatly reduced, and the outfall area would be stabilized. A large scale bio-retention facility would be located in a conspicuous area at the proposed access for the bike lane that will be installed along Preville Avenue. Not only will the project be highly functional for improving water quality, it will also be an attractive community asset that will beautify the area and be a showpiece for green infrastructure. Together with the Preville Green Streets project, this collection of GSI practices will be very important for informing residents and visitors about green infrastructure practices and for reducing pollution inputs to East Creek.

project_info.prj_title: Hurteau river corridor easement - Lamoille River (VRC)
project_info.prj_complete_comments: this state funded NPS project is identified in conjunction with "leveraging"
project_info.prj_overview:
Overview VRC will execute a river corridor easement encompassing approximately 23 acres on the Lamoille River in Fairfax. This grant will specifically cover the easement acquisition costs, stewardship fee, and landowner incentive payment associated with the corridor easement. The purchase of the channel management rights will preclude any future management of the river at this location without the consent of the State and ensure that the river is free to adjust its location within the river corridor in perpetuity.
Objectives Protect river corridor along a portion of Lamoille River; minimize future encroachments and investments in river corridor area; allow river room to adjust; serve as a model for future river corridor protection efforts elsewhere in VT.
Methods As part of the river corridor easement, VRC will create a draft of the easement using the State River Corridor Easement Template (refer to January 2009 Guide to River Corridor Easements). VRC will conduct a survey of the protected property. The survey will provide metes and bounds for Schedule A descriptions of the river corridor, roads, streams crossings, or utilities. VRC will conduct a title search to determine any liens on the property and whether any legal rights of the property or portions of the property have been recorded and, if necessary, will complete mortgage subordination. VRC will monitor the protected property annually to ensure requirements of the easement are being met. VRC will notify landowners of Section III rights under the easement agreement.

status_history.pst_comment: VRC worked with landowners to restore 23.7 acres of floodplain along 1800 feet of Lamoille River in Fairfax. VRC will work with landowner to install & maintain 100 foot vegetated buffer to provide the river with access to its floodplain. Benefits include enhanced flood resilience & WQ improvements by providing sediment and nutrient storage during flodd events.

project_info.prj_title: Jeffersonville easement acquisition - Brewster River

project_info.prj_overview:
Overview Village of Jeffersonville will obtain an easement to ensure continued preservation of critical floodplain storage and water quality enhancement. The continued use of this floodplain as open space will serve as green infrastructure and preserve several floodplain functions it provides that benefit water quality including: maintaining access to the Brewster River¿s floodplain; conveyance of flood flow and slowing the velocity of the water as is spreads over the floodplain; sediment and phosphorus attenuation, during flood events, as they are filtered out by the vegetation and reduced water velocity; and, floodwater infiltration into groundwater.
Objectives Protect riparian lands to avoid future encroachments and investments.
Methods As outlined in overview above, the easement in the floodplain provides several important ecosystem services for the environment that will increase the Village¿s flood resiliency while reducing flood erosion hazards and will help address phosphorus remediation for waters downstream and Lake Champlain.
